<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Jolyon Western (CYS0097)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Jolyon</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Western</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (CYS0097)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CYCLING SAFETY</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – Changing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rule  163</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the Highway code.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">As more cyclists venture onto the road drivers unused to sharing the road with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bicycles  frequently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  treat  cyclists as they would other cars passing within close proximity often at speed.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Currently “Rule 163 of the Highway Code adds that a driver should give cyclists ‘at least as much room’ as you would a car,”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This is far too vague and subjective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignores </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> completely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the inherent difference in the risk involved in passing a four wheele</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d vehicle in which the driver is enclosed in the vehicle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that in passing  a two wheeled vehicle which is subject to wind or road surface  irregularities that can deflect the path of the rider.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">New drivers and indeed current drivers need to be given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">una</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mbiguous  directions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on what a genuinely safe distance to allow is. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">countries ,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Germany &amp; Spain  for example there is a clearly stated 1.5 metre passing standard written into law.  Other areas have mandated minimum 3 ft limit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">yet  the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> UK apparent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly has nothing beyond the bland statement &amp; potentially misleading advice in rule 163.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Changing this to a specific distance and ensuring that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">drivers ,new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and old  become aware of this is a crucial  step in creating a safer environment on our roads for cyc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">les and for car drivers.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Obviously  this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is in the interests of cyclists but  there will be many well-intentioned but  ill-informed  drivers who armed with this awareness may  as a result  not experience the trauma of being involved in what are frequently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">serious or deadly bicycle car collisions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>